<DOC><DOCNO> AP891002-0228 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 2010EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     10-02 0262</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather ,0270</SECOND><HEAD>Showers and Thunderstorms Along the Atlantic Coast</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Light snow fell Monday in parts of Wyoming and Montana, whilerainshowers prevailed elsewhere in the West and from North Carolinato New England.   At least two people were killed when their car was swept away byan overflowing creek near Monroe, N.C.   Surf as high as 12 feet announced the approach of Tropical StormColleen in Guam. The storm strengthened as it moved directly atU.S. territory in the western Pacific.   Eight- to 12-foot waves lashed Guam's southeast coast. About110,000 people live on Guam, 3,800 miles from Honolulu.   Cloudy skies accompanied by scattered showers prevailed fromOregon and northern California to the Dakotas. Light snow fell innorthern Wyoming and southern Montana. California's Sierra Nevadarange had reports of hail or snow pellets in higher elevations,with a half-inch of snow at Mount Rose Ski Resort.   Skies were sunny in the Mississippi Delta to the southwesterndeserts, with gusty winds in Nevada and Arizona. A wind advisorywas posted for the northern half of Arizona.   Early morning fog prevailed east of the Mississippi River, withdense fog reported in Louisiana and Mississippi.   The cold spot in the nation Monday morning was Gunnison, Colo.,with 24 degrees.   Morning lows were in the 60s and 70s across most of the South,dipping to the 20s in northwestern North Dakota and the ColoradoRockies.   Temperatures rose into the 90s in Texas and the Floridapeninsula.   Strong northwesterly winds ushered unseasonably cool air intothe central United States.</TEXT></DOC>